{:level 0, :title "Equipment", :path ["Equipment"], :contents [:div [:p "Besides " [:a {:href "#munitions"} "munitions"] ", there are a number of options when it comes time to outfit your aircraft that enable you to react to and engage in different situations."]], "Avionics and Systems" {:level 1, :title "Avionics and Systems", :path ["Equipment" "Avionics and Systems"], :contents nil, "Multi-Function Color Display" {:level 2, :title "Multi-Function Color Display", :path ["Equipment" "Avionics and Systems" "Multi-Function Color Display"], :contents [:div [:p "With at least two standard on every aircraft, the Multi-Function Color Display " "(" "MFCD" ")" " is your primary means of interaction with the aircraft's systems. While newer aircraft like the " [:a {:href "#f-45a"} "F-45A"] " use a more intuitive touch-screen MFCD, most use a standard MFCD with hardware buttons arrayed along the sides."] [:p "Using a hardware-button MFCD is quite straightforward. The important data will be generally shown in the center of the display, and labels will be positioned adjacent to the buttons. If there is no label next to a button, pressing that button will have no effect."]], "Sensor of Interest" {:level 3, :title "Sensor of Interest", :path ["Equipment" "Avionics and Systems" "Multi-Function Color Display" "Sensor of Interest"], :contents [:div [:p "Some MFCD screens can be made the Sensor of Interest " "(" "SOI" ")" ". If an MFCD screen has this capability, the upper-right-most button will be labeled SOI. Pressing this button will cause the display to be surrounded with a green rectangle to indicate that it is SOI, and any other screen that was previously SOI will no longer be " "(" "there can be only one SOI at a time" ")" ". When SOI, the touchpad/thumbstick of the right controller can be used to control the sensor in a context-dependent way:"] [:table [:thead [:tr [:th {:alignment "left"} "Page "] [:th {:alignment "left"} "Touchpad/thumbstick use"]]] [:tbody [:tr [:td {:alignment "left"} "NAV "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Scroll the map"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "left"} "TGP/EOTS "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Change the camera angle"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "left"} "TSD, RADAR "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Move the cursor and highlight targets; click to select. " "(" "RADAR: click a second time to lock" ")"]]]]]}}, "Radar Warning Receiver" {:level 2, :title "Radar Warning Receiver", :path ["Equipment" "Avionics and Systems" "Radar Warning Receiver"], :contents [:div [:p "The Radar Warning Receiver " "(" "RWR" ")" " system in your aircraft detects hostile radar signals and is used to maintain situational awareness about potential threats. While in real life the RWR will typically include allied radar sources, in VTOLVR they are omitted for simplicity and to reduce clutter."] [:p "The RWR in all aircraft is displayed in a circle, indicating position relative to your aircraft's current orientation. Distance from the center of the circle indicates " [:em "relative threat"] ", with higher " [:em "threat"] " radar sources closer to the center of the circle. " [:em "Position on the RWR does not indicate range"] "."] [:p "Hostile radar sources are indicated on the RWR as a combination of one or two letters/numbols/symbols surrounded by a symbol. The letters inside are an abbreviation indicating the type of threat, while the symbology around it provides more contextual information."] [:p "Table: RWR Symbology"] [:table [:thead [:tr [:th {:alignment "center"} "Symbol "] [:th {:alignment "left"} "Meaning"]]] [:tbody [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:img {:src "/assets/rwr/primary-threat.svg", :alt "Primary Threat"}] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Primary Threat"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:img {:src "/assets/rwr/threat-locked.svg", :alt "Locked Threat"}] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Threat is locked-on or tracking you"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:img {:src "/assets/rwr/new-threat.svg", :alt "Newest Threat"}] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Newest threat"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:img {:src "/assets/rwr/aerial-threat.svg", :alt "Aerial Threat"}] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Aerial " "(" "flying" ")" " threat"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} [:img {:src "/assets/rwr/missile-threat.svg", :alt "Missile Threat"}] " "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Missile lock"]]]] [:ul [:li "The " [:em "primary threat"] " indicates what the system believes to be the most  threatening to your aircraft at the moment."] [:li "A " [:em "tracking threat"] " may fire soon, so listen for warning."] [:li "The " [:em "newest threat"] " can be located in the real world via your HUD/HMCS  if your aircraft has " [:a {:href "#anti-radiation-attack-display"} "ARAD"] " and its display is enabled on the HUD.  New radar threats will be displayed as yellow diamonds on the HUD by ARAD."] [:li "A " [:em "missle lock threat"] " is the only one that displays in a different color,  to make sure you notice it. When you see the red M, you know a hostile  missile has engaged its terminal targeting radar, which generally means  it's about 10 seconds from hitting you."]] [:p "Table: RWR Abbreviations"] [:table [:thead [:tr [:th {:alignment "center"} "Abbreviation "] [:th {:alignment "left"} "Meaning"]]] [:tbody [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "A "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Fire-control radar for Anti-Aircraft Artillery"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "DC "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Drone Cruiser/Carrier"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "DF "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Drone Fighter " "(" "aircraft" ")"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "DM "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Drone Missile ship"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "DS "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "\"Dish, SAM\" The rotating-dish fire-control radar for a SAM"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "E4 "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "AWACS " "(" "Airborne Warning " "&amp;" " Control System" ")"]] [:tr [:td {:alignment "center"} "F "] [:td {:alignment "left"} "Air-to-air Fighter "